  "prompt": "How is the formula for average acceleration determined?",
  "response": "The average acceleration of an object is determined using the change in velocity over a specific time interval. The formula for average acceleration (\\( a_{\\text{avg}} \\)) can be expressed mathematically as:\n\n\\[\na_{\\text{avg}} = \\frac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( \\Delta v \\) is the change in velocity, calculated as the final velocity (\\( v_f \\)) minus the initial velocity (\\( v_i \\)):\n  \\[\n  \\Delta v = v_f - v_i\n  \\]\n- \\( \\Delta t \\) is the time interval during which the change in velocity occurs.\n\nTo summarize, the average acceleration is the rate at which an object\u2019s velocity changes over a specified duration. This formula provides a simple way to quantify how quickly an object speeds up, slows down, or changes direction. It is important to note that average acceleration does not account for any changes that may occur within the time interval; it simply provides an overall effect during that time.",
